{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5fb16423-74bc-4fc5-9998-06e016254405","content":"Here's what you need to change:\n\n**1. NuGet.org — register trusted publisher:**\n- Go to your package → Manage → Publishing → Add Trusted Publisher\n- Select \"GitHub Actions\" and enter your repo owner, name, workflow file, and optionally environment/ref constraints\n\n**2. Workflow — grant OIDC permission and remove the secret:**\n\n```yaml\njobs:\n  publish:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    permissions:\n      id-token: write   # Required for OIDC token\n      contents: read\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n      - uses: actions/setup-dotnet@v4\n        with:\n          dotnet-version: '8.x'\n\n      # Build & pack as usual...\n\n      - name: Push to NuGet\n        run: dotnet nuget push \"**/*.nupkg\" --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n**Key differences from your current setup:**\n\n| Before (API key) | After (OIDC) |\n|---|---|\n| `secrets.NUGET_API_KEY` passed via `--api-key` | No key needed — identity proven via OIDC token |\n| No `permissions` block needed | `id-token: write` required |\n| Key rotation is manual | Token is short-lived & automatic |\n\nThe `dotnet nuget push` command automatically detects the GitHub OIDC token when no `--api-key` is provided and the NuGet source supports trusted publishing.\n\n**3. Clean up:** Once verified, delete the `NUGET_API_KEY` secret from your repo settings.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ab8b88a1-3c74-4072-9a9d-0161c0cc4940","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about switching from using a NuGet API key secret to NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC) in their GitHub Actions publish workflow. This is a general knowledge question about GitHub Actions and NuGet - I don't need to look at any specific files since there's no repository here. Let me provide a concise answer.\n\nNuGet trusted publishing (OIDC) allows GitHub Actions to authenticate with NuGet.org without storing long-lived API keys as secrets. Here's what they need to change:\n\n1. **On NuGet.org**: Configure a trusted publisher for their package, linking it to their GitHub repository/workflow.\n\n\n2. **In their workflow**: Add the `id-token: write` permission to the job, then use the OIDC token for authentication instead of the stored API key secret when running `dotnet nuget push`.\n\nThe key difference is that NuGet needs to exchange the GitHub OIDC token for a temporary credential before the push can happen, rather than using a static API key directly.","outputTokens":793,"requestId":"B82D:246CF2:C89E70:E70CC8:69F2A835"},"id":"64709232-1489-4315-9ad6-5c667965c3ef","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:54:33.095Z","parentId":"0c48b2de-18d6-486f-a9ad-f8c44bd2f6c7"}
